folder: 5th Avenue & Between 64th and 65th Streets, Manhattan, NY
text:
(1)
Fifth Avenue, east side, south from East 65th (left) to 64th (right) Streets, as viewed from the 65th Street transverse road thru Central Park. These structures in 1925 were listed as the properties of the following individuals: Sophie A. Sherman (No. 837); Kate Bover (No. 836); F. Lewisohn (No. 835); A. S. Guggenheimer (No. 833); M. V. Hoggin (No. 830).

March 10, 1929

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A northward view from East 64th Street, showing the site for a modern apartment house, (No. 830 Fifth Avenue) being prepared. This included the entire block front exclusive of the corner structures as shown. The corner house is the James Ben Ali Haggin mansion.

Aug. 15, 1929

P. L. Sperr.

(3)
A view similar to No. 1 but not as inclusive. Note the Sherman house at the S.E. corner of East 65th St. still standing.

April 23, 1938.

P. L. Sperr.

Fifth Ave (left), at the N.E. corner of East 65th Street, showing Temple Emanuel. The congregation consists of members of the upper social strata of New York Jewry. Services are conducted in English.

1936.
W.P.A. Photo.
Federal Writers Project.

Fifth Avenue, at the N.E. corner of East 65th Street, showing at that location the Temple Emanu-El, erected here in 1927 on the former site of the John Jacob Astor mansion. The photographer is viewing same from the 65th Street lateral highway thru Central Park.

This organization was formerly located at the N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue and East 43rd Street in a synagogue erected in 1868. Their earlier meetings were held in the Grand Street Court-room (1845 to 1850). Subsequently they purchased a former church on Chrystie Street and remodeled same for their purpose (1850 to 1856). A Baptist church building on East 12th Street preceded the first Fifth Avenue structure (1856 to 1865).
View 1: May 21, 1933
View 2: April 23, 1938
P. L. Sperr
